from typing import List

class Solution:
    def countSubIslands(self, grid1: List[List[int]], grid2: List[List[int]]) -> int:
        m, n = len(grid1), len(grid1[0])

        def dfs(i, j):
            if i < 0 or i >= m or j < 0 or j >= n or grid2[i][j] == 0:
                return True
            grid2[i][j] = 0  # Mark the cell as visited
            # Check all four directions and ensure all parts of the island in grid2 are also land in grid1
            return (grid1[i][j] == 1) & dfs(i + 1, j) & dfs(i - 1, j) & dfs(i, j + 1) & dfs(i, j - 1)

        count = 0
        for i in range(m):
            for j in range(n):
                if grid2[i][j] == 1 and dfs(i, j):
                    count += 1
        return count
```

This solution uses Depth-First Search (DFS) to explore each island in `grid2` and checks if all the cells of that island are also land in `grid1`. If an island in `grid2` is completely contained within an island in `grid1`, it is counted as a sub-island. The `dfs` function marks visited cells in `grid2` to avoid revisiting them and returns `True` if the current island is a sub-island, otherwise `False`. The main loop iterates through each cell in the grids to find and count sub-islands.
